WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:07.080
Hello, hi everybody, my name is Mark Bennens, I'm heading the Scientific Computing Operations

00:00:07.080 --> 00:00:13.400
at Johnson & Johnson, and I'm also a change leader for adopting R, our open source within

00:00:13.400 --> 00:00:17.040
our company, especially for clinical trials.

00:00:17.040 --> 00:00:21.760
So if you're here today for a change management one-on-one, you're in the right place.

00:00:21.760 --> 00:00:29.959
If you're here today for how to win the lottery, good, it's the same thing.

00:00:29.959 --> 00:00:34.119
First a disclaimer, these are my opinions, it's your responsibility what you do with

00:00:34.119 --> 00:00:40.520
it, and I'm not endorsing any specific products or services.

00:00:40.520 --> 00:00:47.200
What you see on this slide are the five stages of grief, introduced by psychiatrist Elizabeth

00:00:47.200 --> 00:00:54.360
Kubler-Ross in her book on Death and Dying, and these stages represent the emotional journey

00:00:54.560 --> 00:01:00.200
that individuals experience when faced with a life-changing or tragic event.

00:01:00.200 --> 00:01:05.320
Now at J&J, we've been using SAS, statistical analysis software, as you know, for many,

00:01:05.320 --> 00:01:06.639
many years.

00:01:06.639 --> 00:01:12.279
Not that that is a tragic event, but imagine telling a room full of seasoned statistical

00:01:12.279 --> 00:01:19.000
programmers and statisticians who always relied on SAS, that they have to basically switch

00:01:19.160 --> 00:01:24.760
from their beloved SAS to R or Python open source, what would be their response?

00:01:24.760 --> 00:01:30.959
Well, surprise, surprise, they actually go to those five stages.

00:01:30.959 --> 00:01:32.599
First of all, denial.

00:01:32.599 --> 00:01:33.599
This cannot be true.

00:01:33.599 --> 00:01:36.320
SAS is so established and reliable.

00:01:36.320 --> 00:01:39.400
Anger, this is a waste of my time and resources.

00:01:39.400 --> 00:01:43.959
I'm so proficient in SAS and now I have to start over with all these new tools.

00:01:44.120 --> 00:01:49.680
Bargaining, can we just not keep SAS maybe for the data processing and have Python and

00:01:49.680 --> 00:01:50.680
R for visualizations?

00:01:50.680 --> 00:01:56.080
Depression, oh, I'll never be as good in R and Python as I am in SAS.

00:01:56.080 --> 00:01:57.959
And finally, there is acceptance.

00:01:57.959 --> 00:02:01.760
They see the market value because everybody is doing it at other pharma companies and

00:02:01.760 --> 00:02:06.000
there are really opportunities of going to learn open source.

00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:11.839
And during this presentation, I will basically explain how change management can significantly

00:02:11.960 --> 00:02:19.360
help individuals as well as your organization going through emotional stages of change.

00:02:19.360 --> 00:02:21.639
Now how does successful change look like?

00:02:21.639 --> 00:02:28.679
Well, successful change has two basically sides, a technical side and a people side.

00:02:28.679 --> 00:02:33.160
Technical side can also be in processes as well, but just delivering on the technical

00:02:33.160 --> 00:02:34.880
side, that doesn't get it.

00:02:34.880 --> 00:02:39.800
So people really need to embrace, adopt and use the future state for it to be successfully

00:02:39.800 --> 00:02:41.360
implemented.

00:02:41.360 --> 00:02:45.039
And Nicole talked about the technical side of changes, a technical journey.

00:02:45.039 --> 00:02:49.639
Well, I'm going to talk more about the people side of change.

00:02:49.639 --> 00:02:55.399
And I'm going to use as a real life example, going from SAS to R to give you some examples

00:02:55.399 --> 00:02:59.800
on how you can adopt some of the strategies I will explain.

00:02:59.800 --> 00:03:04.940
Now change is not necessarily hard because it's the people side of change.

00:03:04.940 --> 00:03:09.759
It is actually something that you cannot use as sometimes common sense, right?

00:03:09.759 --> 00:03:15.919
And I will be demonstrating that by debunking a myth around change as well.

00:03:15.919 --> 00:03:18.759
How do we do plan, go and manage change effectively?

00:03:18.759 --> 00:03:20.559
Well, I have three phases.

00:03:20.559 --> 00:03:21.559
First of all, we plan.

00:03:21.559 --> 00:03:25.520
I'm going to spend a little bit more time on the planning part because it's sometimes

00:03:25.520 --> 00:03:27.419
that is more overlooked.

00:03:27.419 --> 00:03:32.119
It's about defining the change, understanding the potential impact of the change and creating

00:03:32.119 --> 00:03:35.440
a detailed strategy to go to that process.

00:03:35.440 --> 00:03:40.839
Then implementing the change itself, I can give some tips and tricks there, and then

00:03:40.839 --> 00:03:42.839
eventually sustaining the change.

00:03:42.839 --> 00:03:48.559
So it's not enough to just have people implement it or that we implement the change, but that

00:03:48.559 --> 00:03:53.320
we also reinforce the behaviors and the processes there as well.

00:03:53.320 --> 00:03:56.419
So first of all, the planning phase.

00:03:56.419 --> 00:03:59.080
It's not just enough to start planning for training.

00:03:59.080 --> 00:04:02.039
So why plan for change?

00:04:02.039 --> 00:04:08.279
I don't know if you've ever tried to assemble EKF furniture without any instructions.

00:04:08.279 --> 00:04:15.199
It's like embarking on a heroic quest armed only with an Allen wrench, a screwdriver,

00:04:15.199 --> 00:04:17.320
and I think a vague sense of optimism.

00:04:17.320 --> 00:04:23.519
So you start very confident, convinced that you don't need a manual to only find yourself

00:04:23.519 --> 00:04:29.760
an hour later with a mysterious piles of extra screws, a lopsided bookcase, and I think a

00:04:29.760 --> 00:04:33.920
psychosynching feel that something is terribly wrong here.

00:04:33.920 --> 00:04:39.799
So planning for change is just like writing those EKF instructions, but then for others

00:04:39.799 --> 00:04:45.839
and also better knowing EKF instructions to help avoid that you end up with a wonky outcome

00:04:45.839 --> 00:04:50.799
and that you do basically everything fits together from the start.

00:04:50.799 --> 00:04:56.279
There's a bonus that also most working relationships will hopefully stay intact.

00:04:56.279 --> 00:05:00.640
So yeah, before launching a new software or going with a new programming language,

00:05:00.640 --> 00:05:03.399
please prepare for that change.

00:05:03.399 --> 00:05:07.760
Just providing training is not going to cut it.

00:05:07.760 --> 00:05:10.619
And in planning for change, I like to go over five steps.

00:05:10.619 --> 00:05:15.799
Basically explain the what, the who, the why, any concerns, and also the when.

00:05:15.799 --> 00:05:18.880
So let's start off with the what.

00:05:18.880 --> 00:05:23.920
So in defining the what of the change, you go from a current state to a future state

00:05:23.920 --> 00:05:25.600
and you have a transition.

00:05:25.600 --> 00:05:31.040
But there are four key questions that help explain to other folks what actually the future

00:05:31.040 --> 00:05:33.119
state will be and how you're going to transition.

00:05:33.119 --> 00:05:39.399
And that is, what are the things that we are used to be able to do and still can do?

00:05:39.399 --> 00:05:43.720
Another question is, what are the things that we couldn't do before and still cannot do?

00:05:43.720 --> 00:05:48.519
These two questions are very important because it means that this is business as usual.

00:05:48.519 --> 00:05:52.359
You don't have to change anything there and that calms people down.

00:05:52.359 --> 00:05:54.320
So it's good to explain that as well.

00:05:54.320 --> 00:05:58.380
And then, of course, there are the things that we could do before and can do now.

00:05:58.380 --> 00:05:59.959
So these you have to let go.

00:05:59.959 --> 00:06:03.640
And the things that you couldn't do before and can now.

00:06:03.640 --> 00:06:05.320
So that is where you have to go.

00:06:05.320 --> 00:06:09.320
That's a change that's hopefully giving you a lot of gains.

00:06:09.320 --> 00:06:12.959
So without a clear definition, there is room for ambiguity.

00:06:12.959 --> 00:06:20.440
It can lead to resistance, also confusion, or inefficient use of resources.

00:06:20.440 --> 00:06:22.320
Who is involved in the change?

00:06:22.320 --> 00:06:23.579
So how do we define that?

00:06:24.380 --> 00:06:28.179
These are entities, groups, individuals who are affected by the change.

00:06:28.179 --> 00:06:30.820
Also there, I would divide them into four different groups.

00:06:30.820 --> 00:06:35.859
The ones that are above the change, these can be your sponsors, can be influencers,

00:06:35.859 --> 00:06:37.459
change partners on the change.

00:06:37.459 --> 00:06:42.140
These are mostly the people in your project starting to work out the change.

00:06:42.140 --> 00:06:46.380
The change recipients, those ones will be in the change or going through that journey.

00:06:46.380 --> 00:06:49.500
And then also interesting onlookers around the change.

00:06:49.500 --> 00:06:54.299
Sometimes other departments who are also looking at something you like to implement.

00:06:54.299 --> 00:06:58.339
And identifying these key stakeholders is also an ongoing process.

00:06:58.339 --> 00:07:02.019
For instance, you can have groups who are onlookers and get interested.

00:07:02.019 --> 00:07:04.940
Okay, they're adopting R, they want to use R.

00:07:04.940 --> 00:07:08.380
They might also be, hey, can we not be involved in that journey maybe as well?

00:07:08.380 --> 00:07:11.540
So they change from onlookers to be recipients.

00:07:11.540 --> 00:07:15.179
And also a good thing to look out is for if you have recipients,

00:07:15.179 --> 00:07:17.579
to maybe divide them into subgroups.

00:07:17.579 --> 00:07:22.339
Going from softs to R, you have maybe a subgroup recipients is statisticians.

00:07:22.339 --> 00:07:27.260
You might make a subgroup there of, okay, these are statisticians who already know R

00:07:27.260 --> 00:07:30.220
or these are statisticians who don't know R yet.

00:07:30.220 --> 00:07:36.619
So that helps in defining, okay, you might have to tackle those groups a little bit differently.

00:07:36.619 --> 00:07:39.859
Step three is assessing the impact of change.

00:07:39.859 --> 00:07:42.380
It's not about producing widgets or features.

00:07:42.380 --> 00:07:45.019
So it's not about, it's about changing behavior.

00:07:45.019 --> 00:07:50.260
I give an example, if you put in a sign to say people to turn right,

00:07:50.260 --> 00:07:52.459
that doesn't mean that people are going to turn right.

00:07:52.459 --> 00:07:55.859
So the widget is there, but it doesn't mean that the behavior is changing

00:07:55.859 --> 00:07:57.540
and that people are turning right.

00:07:57.540 --> 00:08:00.019
So it's all about the outcomes itself.

00:08:00.019 --> 00:08:04.179
And you can explain it very well, the impact for people with pains to gain.

00:08:04.179 --> 00:08:08.500
So what is for them to gain?

00:08:08.500 --> 00:08:14.100
And that explains it a little bit more from the emotional side than from the technical side.

00:08:14.100 --> 00:08:18.660
At heart is, yeah, the question that we need to answer is for what's in it for me.

00:08:18.660 --> 00:08:21.739
And you need to do that uniquely for each stakeholder.

00:08:21.739 --> 00:08:25.779
So for instance, from going from SAS to R, you can explain to statisticians

00:08:25.779 --> 00:08:32.460
that they have a wider range of advanced statistical packages and libraries

00:08:32.460 --> 00:08:34.059
to their availability.

00:08:34.059 --> 00:08:39.020
And that gives them cutting edge, gives them access to cutting edge methods.

00:08:39.020 --> 00:08:45.219
And that from a statistician's perspective can really help.

00:08:45.219 --> 00:08:50.260
The fourth step is developing strategies for managing resistance.

00:08:50.260 --> 00:08:55.219
Well, people might say we've always done it in this way and it works fine with SAS.

00:08:55.219 --> 00:09:00.859
Well, they're often expressing a variety of underlying sentiments and perceptions.

00:09:00.859 --> 00:09:04.820
They have a sense of loss of control, they're uncertain, it's something new.

00:09:04.820 --> 00:09:07.940
They might fear of failure, doubts that it might work

00:09:07.940 --> 00:09:11.900
because they have already gone through past failures.

00:09:11.900 --> 00:09:14.140
They don't see the problem with the current process.

00:09:14.140 --> 00:09:21.340
So people resist for many, many different reasons and can also be very personal as well.

00:09:21.340 --> 00:09:25.380
So some examples, if you move from SAS to R, what you can put in place for the resistance

00:09:25.380 --> 00:09:30.500
is a support team, SMEs that you can put in place to really help guide

00:09:30.500 --> 00:09:34.539
and hold the hands of people in that process.

00:09:34.539 --> 00:09:39.979
Pilot projects to gain, people need to gain some experience in it

00:09:39.979 --> 00:09:42.859
and maybe do also gradual transition.

00:09:42.859 --> 00:09:47.659
So not putting in a hard deadline for people.

00:09:47.659 --> 00:09:51.739
But also an escalation process may be in place because some of the concerns

00:09:51.739 --> 00:09:53.780
that people have, you need to listen to them.

00:09:53.780 --> 00:10:00.299
They might be actually valid reasons why they are a little bit hold back to do that change.

00:10:00.299 --> 00:10:03.340
Give an example, there might be clinical trials which are so,

00:10:03.340 --> 00:10:08.179
and need to be done so fast that it might be better to do an exception and opt out

00:10:08.179 --> 00:10:13.460
and say, okay, just do that study still in SAS.

00:10:13.460 --> 00:10:15.140
Let's debunk a myth.

00:10:15.140 --> 00:10:17.059
Education will change behavior.

00:10:17.059 --> 00:10:18.859
So we're always thinking about training.

00:10:18.859 --> 00:10:20.900
Let's give the right information.

00:10:20.900 --> 00:10:26.059
Let's tell people, okay, this is a great idea and it's all the best you can do.

00:10:26.059 --> 00:10:32.020
Well, it's actually not the education and information that will lead to changing behavior.

00:10:32.020 --> 00:10:36.739
It's actually the actions and opinions of others called social norms

00:10:36.739 --> 00:10:41.380
that influence the behavior of people to the greatest extent.

00:10:41.380 --> 00:10:43.739
And street musicians, they know that.

00:10:43.739 --> 00:10:48.059
So they, when they play, they already have their case with money in there.

00:10:48.059 --> 00:10:50.580
Just to give you an example, while other people have donated,

00:10:50.580 --> 00:10:52.299
maybe you should donate as well.

00:10:52.299 --> 00:10:55.739
What street musicians a little bit forget is if you would have a friend passing

00:10:55.739 --> 00:10:59.140
by every five minutes and dropping some money in it,

00:10:59.140 --> 00:11:02.780
that would even more convince other people to dropping money in it.

00:11:02.780 --> 00:11:05.539
So it's the same way going from SAS to R.

00:11:05.539 --> 00:11:09.260
If you have experienced peoples in your team, start doing it and explaining

00:11:09.260 --> 00:11:10.979
to other how great and how good it is.

00:11:10.979 --> 00:11:15.580
And that might help actually to convince other people to start doing it as well.

00:11:15.580 --> 00:11:18.700
So actions and opinions of other called social norms,

00:11:18.700 --> 00:11:23.940
that's what influences our behavior to the greatest extent.

00:11:23.940 --> 00:11:25.780
And the last step is the one.

00:11:25.780 --> 00:11:31.460
So that's basically making a roadmap that provides a clear structure,

00:11:31.460 --> 00:11:34.539
ensures that all the stakeholders understand their roles and

00:11:34.539 --> 00:11:39.059
responsibilities, and that the behavioral expectations placed upon them

00:11:39.059 --> 00:11:41.979
at various stages of the transformation.

00:11:41.979 --> 00:11:46.260
So including key milestones, tasks, is essential for

00:11:46.260 --> 00:11:48.580
successful realization of change.

00:11:48.580 --> 00:11:54.380
So it gives a good view of it and definitely a clear structure.

00:11:54.380 --> 00:11:58.059
All right, let's go with the next phase, that's implementing the change.

00:11:58.059 --> 00:12:02.340
Some of the key things I would like to highlight there is that communication

00:12:02.340 --> 00:12:07.659
is key in that perspective, but also be honest and transparent when you communicate.

00:12:07.659 --> 00:12:09.979
So sometimes you need to give the bad news as well.

00:12:11.700 --> 00:12:15.179
So don't sugarcoat it, just mention it like it is.

00:12:15.179 --> 00:12:18.859
Use also multiple channels of communication, like not only email, but

00:12:18.859 --> 00:12:22.659
also maybe Yammer, maybe a SharePoint as well.

00:12:22.659 --> 00:12:26.179
And there's also something, don't give the message once.

00:12:26.179 --> 00:12:30.299
People might not read the email, people might not read the Yammer page.

00:12:30.299 --> 00:12:35.340
So we know for a fact that you have to repeat the messages seven to nine times

00:12:35.340 --> 00:12:37.820
for it to really start sticking, and that's a lot.

00:12:40.140 --> 00:12:45.020
Also monitor your change because you really want to know how basically you're progressing.

00:12:45.020 --> 00:12:48.900
So from going from soft to R, you have a statistical computing environment,

00:12:48.900 --> 00:12:53.979
you can crank the numbers out and how many people are actually using R already.

00:12:53.979 --> 00:12:57.539
Because there might be people that are not doing it yet, and you might have to talk

00:12:57.539 --> 00:13:02.859
with them, listen to them, or see how you can best support them in their change.

00:13:02.859 --> 00:13:08.179
This besides communication and monitoring, give plenty of support.

00:13:08.179 --> 00:13:14.700
It's really important to have resources available for holding the hands of people

00:13:14.700 --> 00:13:21.260
going through that process, that they really feel they're not alone in that whole process.

00:13:21.260 --> 00:13:24.460
And then lastly, sustaining the change.

00:13:24.460 --> 00:13:25.900
It's not a one-time event.

00:13:25.900 --> 00:13:27.700
It's an ongoing process.

00:13:27.700 --> 00:13:33.260
So you'll possibly have to do some additional trainings again, reinforcing

00:13:33.260 --> 00:13:37.179
the behavior, support the people along the way.

00:13:37.179 --> 00:13:43.380
Maybe also be flexible and willing to do some adjustments to your plan as well.

00:13:43.380 --> 00:13:46.539
Tell success stories and reward people for it.

00:13:46.539 --> 00:13:51.500
Also very important to sustain the change.

00:13:51.500 --> 00:13:56.820
And then last but not least, I would like to talk about branding and infusing some fun into it.

00:13:56.820 --> 00:14:03.539
So creating the right buzz about the change is something that people get engaged and want to get involved in.

00:14:03.539 --> 00:14:09.099
Personally, I really like the theme, my change and what we've done here going from soft to R.

00:14:09.099 --> 00:14:14.659
We rebranded our change initiative to SAIL to R or SAIL.R.

00:14:14.659 --> 00:14:21.859
We call our meeting Sailor Trips, where we sail the seas of open source together.

00:14:21.859 --> 00:14:24.580
So maybe you recognize some familiar faces.

00:14:24.580 --> 00:14:30.380
We really took in person a photo from everybody with a sailor cap on.

00:14:30.380 --> 00:14:33.820
And then we had AI put in all the different suits.

00:14:34.500 --> 00:14:42.659
So yeah, you might have recognized maybe JJ Hadley, Dhariv, Jason and Phil.

00:14:42.659 --> 00:14:46.219
So yeah, this is our last slide about change management.

00:14:46.219 --> 00:14:51.739
So I would like you to remember that know your stakeholders and what's in it for them.

00:14:51.739 --> 00:14:55.739
People are not wired for change, so resistance is to be expected.

00:14:55.739 --> 00:14:58.059
Education will not change behavior.

00:14:58.059 --> 00:15:00.219
Communication is a tourist street.

00:15:00.219 --> 00:15:03.340
And brand and infuse some fun.

00:15:03.340 --> 00:15:06.059
So thank you all for your time and attention today.

00:15:06.059 --> 00:15:09.539
And please don't hesitate to reach out if you have any questions.

00:15:09.539 --> 00:15:10.539
So thank you.

00:15:17.940 --> 00:15:22.539
Great, we do have some questions from the virtual audience.

00:15:22.539 --> 00:15:29.260
So how did you handle the people very hesitant or even against change?

00:15:29.419 --> 00:15:33.500
We have to, yeah, what we did is talking a lot with those people and seeing what

00:15:33.500 --> 00:15:38.099
actually why they are hesitant and maybe we can support them, maybe we can help them.

00:15:38.099 --> 00:15:41.659
And like I said before, we also have that escalation process.

00:15:41.659 --> 00:15:46.099
So there are people who may be resistant for a right reason, then we also need to,

00:15:46.099 --> 00:15:50.820
okay, this is what you need to, we need to adopt a little bit for them.

00:15:50.820 --> 00:15:55.140
On the other hand, we do require people also to move as well.

00:15:55.140 --> 00:15:56.619
So it is a strategy.

00:15:56.619 --> 00:15:59.659
So some people do need a gentle nudge in that case.

00:16:04.780 --> 00:16:08.619
So another question, how do you generally determine resourcing

00:16:08.619 --> 00:16:10.659
for a change management effort?

00:16:10.659 --> 00:16:14.460
For example, is it a team of one or is there a general structure to follow?

00:16:14.460 --> 00:16:16.260
We do have a change management team.

00:16:16.260 --> 00:16:20.500
And then depending on, because in our case, we moved trial by trial.

00:16:20.500 --> 00:16:25.059
That means that we have a support group depending on when those trials are moving.

00:16:25.059 --> 00:16:28.619
We do have additional resources in place and also SMEs.

00:16:28.619 --> 00:16:32.500
So a support network of subject matter experts in place as well.

00:16:36.059 --> 00:16:38.580
We have a few questions, so I'm just going to keep coming up here.

00:16:39.700 --> 00:16:43.780
Have you used any specific resources for SAS programmers transitioning into Arc?

00:16:46.780 --> 00:16:47.739
Yes.

00:16:47.739 --> 00:16:52.460
So what we do is we have a team of change agents as well.

00:16:52.619 --> 00:16:56.780
We do have SharePoint websites where we put a lot of information on.

00:16:57.140 --> 00:16:59.739
Also, I think there is a Canvas project where we have the

00:16:59.739 --> 00:17:01.299
differences between SAS and Arc.

00:17:01.299 --> 00:17:06.859
So we really explain everything to the people and we have additional support

00:17:06.859 --> 00:17:09.020
people available that can help out.

00:17:09.020 --> 00:17:12.180
So teams can jump in if they really have any questions.

00:17:12.420 --> 00:17:12.939
So, yes.

00:17:19.380 --> 00:17:19.699
Great.

00:17:19.939 --> 00:17:26.420
So two large pharma companies made public top-down announcements about

00:17:26.420 --> 00:17:28.859
their goals replacing SAS with R and filings.

00:17:30.060 --> 00:17:32.420
Was that captured in your roadmap internally or

00:17:32.420 --> 00:17:33.819
considered as a public statement?

00:17:36.060 --> 00:17:39.979
We do look into, yeah, what those companies have done.

00:17:40.060 --> 00:17:42.780
And we also try to connect to those companies as well

00:17:42.780 --> 00:17:44.180
and learn from them also.

00:17:44.660 --> 00:17:45.020
Yes.

00:17:46.099 --> 00:17:48.380
So it's not, we're not alone in that, in that situation.

00:17:48.500 --> 00:17:48.819
Correct.

00:17:50.219 --> 00:17:50.300
Yeah.

00:18:02.540 --> 00:18:04.180
A question about deadlines.

00:18:04.339 --> 00:18:09.859
So you mentioned that there are sometimes no hard deadlines.

00:18:10.939 --> 00:18:12.420
They tend to be useful though.

00:18:12.420 --> 00:18:16.819
So how do you ensure completion without a hard deadline?

00:18:20.699 --> 00:18:26.140
We give people the time to transition, but that doesn't mean there is no timeline.

00:18:26.140 --> 00:18:27.380
There's no clear deadline.

00:18:27.380 --> 00:18:31.859
There's no flick of a switch, I would say, from going to SAS to R, but we are

00:18:31.859 --> 00:18:34.420
moving people in a certain direction.

00:18:34.459 --> 00:18:35.459
I give an example.

00:18:35.459 --> 00:18:39.500
There are some studies that we say first patient in from that day,

00:18:39.699 --> 00:18:42.020
those people will have to move to R.

00:18:42.140 --> 00:18:46.459
So there is a gentle requirement to moving to R, but that doesn't mean that

00:18:46.500 --> 00:18:49.900
you need everybody or there's one fixed deadline.

00:18:49.979 --> 00:18:54.300
You can have multiple deadlines for different stakeholders involved.

00:18:59.459 --> 00:19:01.380
We have one more question here we can end it off with.

00:19:01.739 --> 00:19:04.260
One of the benefits of using R and open source software is

00:19:04.260 --> 00:19:05.619
quick change implementation.

00:19:05.939 --> 00:19:09.420
Did you try to wrap a general quote unquote flexibility to handle

00:19:09.420 --> 00:19:10.540
change into your trainings?

00:19:10.939 --> 00:19:14.540
Well, we have a clear process in our statistical computing environment.

00:19:14.579 --> 00:19:18.060
And yes, there are also some updates containers from technical perspective.

00:19:18.060 --> 00:19:21.819
Yes, there are some flexibility in there and we also have a development

00:19:21.819 --> 00:19:25.099
environment so that new code that you really want to use, you can install

00:19:25.099 --> 00:19:26.300
it and you can start using with it.

00:19:26.300 --> 00:19:28.020
So yes, there is some flexibility.

00:19:29.459 --> 00:19:29.939
Thank you.

00:19:29.939 --> 00:19:30.260
Thank you.

